A Republican strategy to counter the reelection of Obama
The leaders of the Republicans justify their policy with the need to combat electoral fraud.
However, the Brennan Center considers the latter to be a myth by confirming that the election fraud in the United States is more rare than the number of people killed by lightning.
In addition, in 10 years, the Republican lawyers have recorded only 300 cases of election fraud in the United States.
One thing is certain: these new provisions will have a negative impact on election participation.
In this sense, these measures partially undermine the democratic system of the United States.
Unlike Canada, the U.S. states are responsible for conducting the elections in each country.
In this sense, since 2009, the majority of American governments have proclaimed new laws that make the process of registration or urnishing difficult.
This phenomenon has gained importance after the November 2010 elections, in which 675 new Republican representatives were registered in 26 states.
As a result, 180 bills were introduced in 2011 alone, restricting the exercise of the right to vote in 41 states.
The new electoral laws require voters to present a photo ID and proof of US citizenship.
In addition, these laws also shorten the periods for the early vote, declare the right to register as voters on the day of the election, and allow citizens to agree on the right to vote for which a court act exists.
Before the 2006 elections, no U.S. State requested the voters to show a photo ID.
Indiana was the first state to claim such a claim.
The United States Supreme Court confirmed the constitutionality of Indiana's law in 2008.
The Republican authorities hurried to extend this practice to other countries.
Over the past two years, they have promoted bills in 34 states that force voters to show a photo ID.
It is important to note that, in contrast to Quebec, US citizens do not have a universal ID card like the health insurance card.
Indeed, 11% of US citizens, i.e. 21 million electors, do not have any photo ID issued by a government authority of their state.
In addition, five million new voters in 2012 do not have such a ID.
However, more than a hundred dollars are often payable to obtain the required ID.
The new restrictions are disproportionately affected by young people, minorities and people with low income.
In fact, 25% of African Americans, 15% of people with a income of less than $35,000, 18% of citizens over 65, and 20% of voters between 18 and 29, do not have the required photo ID.
This is more than that.
Students who are regarded as voters who give their voice more for democratic candidates are not allowed in several countries to use their photo ID issued by their institution.
On the other hand, the same States allow members of fishing or hunting clubs who choose more for the Republican side to use the cards issued by these clubs for elections.
Before 2004, no federal government has requested proof of citizenship for the election.
Arizona was the first state to introduce such a claim.
Since 2011, a dozen states have adopted laws that require voters to demonstrate their US citizenship.
These measures are clearly aimed at limiting Spanish votes.
For it is clear that two out of three Spanish voters prefer the democratic party.
In addition, in 2011, Republican legislators in eight states promoted laws that abolished the registration of voters on the election day.
In addition, you have limited the right of individuals and groups to assist those electors who wish to register.
These restrictions are not without consequences.
For example, the campaigns to register voters during the 2004 general elections have contributed to the registration of approximately 10 million citizens.
Because the measures adopted since 2009 have reduced the proportion of new voters registered in 2010 by 17% compared to 2006.
In addition, the Republican legislators have adopted laws in five other federal states aimed at shortening the period for the early vote.
For example, in the 2008 general elections in Florida, 33% of the voters who voted in advance were Afro-Americans, although they are only 13% of the federal voters.
The same applies to the Spanish population.
The latter represented only 11% of the voters, but 24% of the citizens who elected in advance.
On the other hand, the whites, who represented 76% of the voters, accounted for only 46% of the voters who chose in advance.
Of course, the democratic legislators and their followers have strongly opposed the adoption of laws that restrict the registration of voters.
Several bills were blocked by the vetos of democratic governors.
The US Attorney General has intervened to suspend the most controversial laws.
They could partially limit the damage.
For example, only 16 of the 34 states have adopted laws requiring the display of a photo ID.
However, the new rules introduced in 2012 will undoubtedly complicate the exercise of the right to vote.
Democrat critics praise the party-political nature of the laws adopted and see in them as a clear objective the influence of the results in the countries that decide for 2012.
A report by the Brennan Center from 2011 shows that the states that adopted these laws represent 171 of the 270 votes required in the electoral panel to win the Presidency.
It is too early to confirm with certainty that these changes to the legislation in the electoral system will have a significant impact on the outcome of the presidential elections in 2012.
But one thing is certain: these new provisions will have a negative impact on voting participation.
In this sense, these measures partially undermine the democratic system of the United States.
