The Higgs Boson analyzes
The announcement of the likely discovery of the Higgs Bosons has given rise to a certain apprehension last summer, and this for good reason.
In fact, it is believed that this Boson is involved in nothing less than in the mechanism responsible for the mass of all objects in the universe.
And finally, it is the last particle whose existence has been predicted by the standard model - our best or least false explanation of nature and the behaviour of matter - but has not yet been observed empirically.
But for the physicists, it is not yet entirely sure that it is really the Higgs.
We know without any doubt that we have a real new particle, and that it resembles the Higgs Boson predicted by the standard model.
In addition, this seems to be confirmed by new data presented this week at a major physics congress in Kyoto, but data are still missing to be absolutely safe.
But let's assume that it's actually the Higgs, because there seems to be only a small risk of deception, and let's look at what's going on.
There is an inevitable law in this world, which results in that two objects cannot be present at the same time.
It is not possible to violate this rule - and do not try it too strong because you will hurt yourself.
For even if particle physics is a truly strange world, it turns out that they also have such a law: the Pauli's principle of exclusion, which states that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time when they are in the same "quota state", with this "state" in general consisting of some of their properties.
On the basis of this, the physicists divide the particles into two categories.
In a corner are the good citizens who are called fermiones and are steadfastly obeying the Pauli principle.
And in the other, the Bosons are moving, a bad band of anarchists to whom nothing is sacred - certainly not this principle, which means that they can actually be at the same time at the same time.
According to the website The Particle Adventure of the Berkeley laboratories (which is absolutely surprising) these bosons are divided into two groups: the mesons we will not treat here and the "power particles" through which the great forces of nature spread and with which the Higgs boson would be related.
But it must be emphasised here that these bosones are not all such exotic creatures as you could think.
If you are able to read this chronology, then only thanks to a boson of exceptional banality: the photon or the "light particle", which is the "bottom" of the electromagnetic force.
In fact, when a particle accelerates with an electric charge or changes the direction, the electromagnetic field is "disrupted" exactly in this place, in like a silicon stone thrown into a pond.
This "disruption" creates an electromagnetic wave (light, infrared or ultraviolet radiation, etc.), and this wave is nothing but a photon and thus one of the bosons "dragers of power".
More stable field
The same applies to the Higgs Boson, with the difference that another field, the Higgs field, needs to be "disrupted" so that this Boson appears.
However, the Higgs field is much more stable than the electromagnetic field; the pathogen must achieve very high energies, a little similar to a frozen pond whose surface could only be frightened by a very large rock.
Therefore, a huge particle accelerator such as the CERN is needed - the Large Hadron Collider is a 27 km ring! - to achieve such energy.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is again helpful to explain the relationship between the higgs and the mass.
In fact, it is not all particles and not all materials that interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, such as magnets, do this, but others do not - for example, a sheet of paper would never hold onto the refrigerator itself.
And not all particles also interact with the Higgs field: those who do it have a mass, while the others (as well as the photon) do not have a mass.
For what can all these research be "good," Mrs Plamondon asks?
For science, they are used to review the standard model (SM), and they also allow physicists to examine all differences between the observations and the predictions of the SM.
There are many physicists who are most likely to hope that such deviations will be found, since the smallest difference could open a door to a "new physics" and stop some holes in the model.
It has to be said that the latter still has major deficiencies, as it does not provide an explanation for gravity (ups!) and dark matter that forms about 80% of the matter of the universe (renews ups!).
However, such deviations have not yet been found in the CERN.
Effects
The impact of this research on the general population is more difficult to predict, but it would be wrong to assume that there would be no.
By the way, in the early 1960s, the laser pioneers in the Bell laboratories did not suspect that their work would trigger such a revolution.
They saw scientific applications, but nothing else.
Indeed, the deceased physicist Willard Boyle - who worked in the Bell Labs, in which the laser was invented in the 1960s, and who himself developed the first permanent strip laser (the first were pulsed) in 1962 - has already said that the laser was seen as a "lab play" at the beginning.
Imagine...
Applications can also be made from all the instruments surrounding research.
For example, Willard Boyle developed a small light sensor during his work in the optics in 1969.
Although it wasn't the original purpose, this sensor today serves all digital cameras worldwide as "eye" and introduced him the Nobel Prize for Physics in 2009.
Of course, this does not mean that the activities of the LHC will necessarily change our life, but it means that you can really never know it...
Palliative care - the best way to die...
Quebec recently discussed the delicate issue of the end of life with its committee for "Death in dignity".
The debate will have to be resumed shortly, although a bill is being prepared.
However, much remains to be done in this important area.
Le Devoir has tried to look at this more closely.
A few weeks ago, Mr. L. lived alone in his apartment in the Montérégie.
The prostate cancer that raised him had left him a period of two years.
"They gave me five years to live, I've done seven years," he said half-heartedly, lying in his bed in the home for palliative care Victor-Gadbois in Bel eye, where he arrived the day before.
"However, it's always a shock, you can't be prepared for it," he says.
The disease does its work: an immense weakness prevents him from going to the toilet alone and even eating himself.
Sitting at the table in front of a delicious lunch, he accepts to be helped with the dinner.
He is courageously able to smile and talk to the strangers who are busy around him, bring his medicines to him, and offer him a bath.
The courage of ordinary death.
"My greatest desire is that my diarrhoea be cured because this is humiliating," he says.
A few hours later, the team found a cure for this evil.
"In the course of our life we learn that a man is pinking in standing," says Pierre Brodeur, a psychologist at the Victor-Gadbois home.
Returning to the childhood phase is an unacceptable humiliation for some people.
"This depends on the ability of the person," he finds a step back.
In the opinion of several people working in palliative care, large events take place in the middle of these steps.
Patients who are sent to the home for palliative care Victor-Gadbois all suffer from cancer.
They have a maximum life expectancy of three months.
At this stage they are no longer accumulated by the doctors and nurses who care for them with so-called "healing" care.
For Ms. A., 89 years old, the worst fear is to die "consciously and by suffocation".
But through the disease, I really met my children.
"I have good children," she adds.
"I don't have any desires in life," she says before she accepts that she is put on a mask that helps her breathe.
She still expects a last visit to her son, who comes from Italy, in the next few days.
In the Victor-Gadbois home, you can offer a group of volunteers and help in eating food.
Palliative care is used when there are no other options.
To make death more pleasant.
In Quebec, 11700 people have a bed for palliative care.
That's very little when you take into account that one day we're all going to die.
Here life continues under the best possible conditions, explains Dr. Christiane Martel, one of the doctors of the home.
Both at the level of physical, emotional or spiritual comfort.
The dying person can be treated with Brandy or Pepsi as desired.
Diabetic patients no longer need to control their blood sugar levels.
And death is part of everyday life.
Last night we served Mr X a beer that died during the night.
This morning his son will drink the beer to the feet of the deceased.
"We also help family and patients," says Care Director Nathalie Savard.
In the Victor-Gadbois home is no day like the other.
In addition to an old man of 93 years, who enjoys the last family meeting in the courtyard and is well supported by his pillows, while hitting his honor, a 36-year-old young man, surrounded by his parents, his wife and his two little children, dies tragically after he tried everything to survive.
"For six months, three to five beds have always been filled with cancer patients under the age of 45," says Dr. Christiane Martel.
53% of patients sent to the Victor-Gadbois home come from their residence, 47% from the hospital.
Problem of access to palliative care
It is said that 77% of Canadians do not have access to palliative care, i.e. to care to alleviate the suffering of patients when the latter have reached the final stage of their life, both at home, in hospital or in a nursing home.
And several organizations, such as the Victor-Gadbois home and the Society for Domestic Palliative Care in the Montreal area, are more or less specialised exclusively in the care of cancer patients.
Exactly this large shortcoming in Quebec's health care ensures that several specialist doctors in palliative care look forward to the adoption of a law on the regulation of death relief and assisted suicide with concern.
Since October, a manifest has been in circulation, signed by prominent personalities of palliative care such as Dr. Balfour Mount and Dr. Bernard Lapointe to demonstrate their opposition to such an initiative.
According to Dr. Christiane Martel, Quebec's health system is not efficient enough to ensure that everyone has the right to a high-quality palliative care before accepting death relief.
Recently, she says, I saw a patient who was 14 days with great pain in emergency, without taking measures to relieve her.
I fear that patients only want to die because they do not receive adequate health care.
And at the same time, several oncologists treat their patients broken despite worst forecasts until the last day.
Helene Richard's chances of survival were already minimal when she discontinued a difficult chemotherapy.
When I told my oncologist that I will stop the treatment, she answered me that she regrets that I will give up the fight, she told me.
However, she had told me that I was at the end!
No omnipotent care
Dr. Martel believes that 90% of the patients who asked to die thank the nurses that they did not accept this desire after their pains have been eased by a team of palliative care.
However, it must be clearly stated that palliative care is not omnipotent in pain treatment.
According to Elsie Monereau, head of the Palliative Care Society, 8% of patients do not respond to pain treatment.
At the end of the life, the doctors often rely on the terminal sedation, which results in either spontaneous or permanent sedation of the patient until the time of his death.
We can no longer act as if we do not perceive this side of suffering.
Patients without pain relief will be more and more likely to resort to this terminal sedation.
Patients whose pain is not alleviated say the same sentence: "I want to die."
But that doesn't necessarily mean "I want you to sleep in me", but "I want my pain to be alleviated".
