With Bitcoin, all net nodes are at the same time bookkeepers, auditors, issuers and buyers and sellers.
How does this network work?
Each transaction between two users takes place between two e-mail addresses in the form of an e-mail.
With the difference that the user can choose another address for each payment, which ensures anonymity.
A series of data related to this transaction is signed electronically by a double encryption system.
In this way, the network can verify the authenticity of the transaction.
Using the contents of the file, it is also possible to ensure that the traded bitcoins are present in the public accounts account that is spread throughout the network.
The crucial step is to record this new transaction in this book.
This is done through a mathematical task that is started on the computers, with the winner, who is a kind of provisional central banker, having the privilege to add this additional line.
This is a fragmentation of the file, i.e. converting a large file into a shorter and unambiguous electronic fingerprint.
The computers "take" the new transaction and add it a number before the whole is "hackt".
The goal is to find the number that gives a special fingerprint (multiple zeros at the beginning).
If this number has been found, the other nodes can easily check if it is the right number.
The transaction is therefore permanently linked to the chain of all other transactions, and any modification would change the fingerprint.
If one user wants to pay with the same money twice (less than 10 minutes) to cheat, only one of the two transactions would be validated by the network and the other would remain without connection, as both have different fingerprints.
The computer that has solved the task receives 50 bitcoins.
