Poland and space.
Last week, Poland was the twentieth member of this space authority at a ministerial meeting of the European Space Agency ESA member countries. Poland is thus the second member of the former Eastern Block (in the Czech Republic, which became a member of the ESA on 12 November 2008).
Poland started close cooperation with ESA in 1994 and participated in several ESA projects in the following years.
The way of Poland into space, of course, began much earlier.
Even before World War II, Polish cosmos enthusiasts worked on space, not always with understanding.
For example, I recall the lecture by A. Šternfeld of 6 December 1933 at the Warsaw Observatory, in which the author presented thoughts from his pioneering work "Input to Cosmonautics".
However, the ideas of the young engineer (born 1905) left the listeners cold, and after years Šternfeld remembered that only Dr. Jan Gadomski had shown interest in his work.
In 1934 Šternfeld won the REP-hirsch Prize, founded by Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch, for "Input to Cosmonautics".
Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966) later became an important defender of astronomy and space.
In Polish magazines he published hundreds of articles and wrote several books about these scientific disciplines.
Gadomski's worldwide recognized contribution to space development was recognized, among other things, by the name of one of the craters on the earthly side of the moon after him.
Already in 1925 a railway drain was built in Poland for which a rocket drive was planned.
Unfortunately, the author of the draft and the details of this project remained unknown.
It is not even clear whether the rocket should be used to start or brake the drains.
The information for this purpose comes exclusively from the contemporary press.
In 1933 the Polish infantry began to deal with rocket-operated shots.
The research was carried out by the Institut Komórka Techniki Uzbrojenia in cooperation with Prof. Mieczyslaw Wolfke and Prof. Gustaw Mokrzyckiegi.
From the documents supplied it is clear that the research was premature to the stage of practical tests.
Research was then obviously interrupted by the entry of the German Wehrmacht.
In 1937 the design of a photoelectric hunting dragon from Ing. Rohoziński appeared in the press, and in the following year the work "Rakieta - torpeda powietrzna i rakietobomba lotnicza" of the author Leliwa-Krzywoblocky appeared.
Both projects concerned the military use of the missile drive.
Shortly before the war, all projects on military use of rocket technology were coordinated by the Transitional Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Committee Doradczo-Naukowy).
The committee was set up in 1937, but after two years of work, its work was terminated by the beginning of the war.
Further articles on space appeared after the war thanks to the work of the Polish Space Society (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne) in the Polish press.
The first mention of this society takes place in 1954 in the November edition of the magazine Problemy, in which four extensive articles are devoted to space.
The article by Prof. M. Subotowicz contains the proposal to establish a space society.
At that time there were already the first projects on satellite technology, and it was foreseen that space research would have a future.
Already at its beginnings in 1956, the Polish space company PTA tried to join the International Space Federation, founded in 1951, and in fact PTA became an ordinary member already in autumn 1956.
The following year was the first PTA president, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959), Deputy Chairman of the International Space Federation.
He had this office until his death in 1959.
Since 1956, the PTA has played a major role in the development of the highly successful meteorological rocket (Rakieta Meteorologiczna), the first Polish rocket for scientific research.
The first type, the RM-1, was completed in 1957 and the first launch took place on October 10, 1958.
The rocket with a maximum flight height of 1800 m was about 80 cm long and weighed not entirely 5 kg.
Later, an improved version, the RM-1A, was built, and in 1959, in the B.Dów wilderness, flight tests started with the two-stage RM-2 rocket.
The rocket was 1.4 m long and weighed about 11.5 kg.
Another stage of development should already be able to do real scientific work - the RM-34 rocket should reach a flight height of up to 14.5 km and be used to observe elevation winds.
However, in 1962 the further development was discontinued.
The first RM rocket was replaced by the Meteor-1 rocket developed between 1962 and 1965.
The rocket was designed as a two-stage rocket, its total length was 510 cm and the starting weight was 32.5 kg.
Three types (Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) of this rocket were developed, which differed from one another in the size of the transport space for scientific instruments.
The Meteor-1A rocket had a transport space with a capacity of 0.4 litres, Meteor-1B over 0.34 litres and Meteor-1C over 0.62 litres.
The maximum flight height was 37 km for all three types.
Between 1965 and 1968 the Meteor 2 rocket was developed at the aviation institute, whose first flight tests began in October 1970.
Meteor-2 had a starting weight of 380 kg and was able to transport a 10 kg operating load to an altitude of about 60 km.
Subsequently, the Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 versions were built.
It is also worth mentioning Poland's accession to the COSPAR Committee for Space Research in 1960, which followed the establishment of a national COSPAR committee two years later.
Poland also participated in space research with Soviet satellites within the Intercosmos programme, and in 1978 the Polish pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became the second intercosmonaut after the Czech Vladimír Remek.
