Germany abstained in the vote on the inclusion of Palestine.
According to Stephen Szabo, an expert on US-European relations, Berlin is balancing this at a narrow diplomacy level.
Deutsche Welle: At the beginning of the week Germany had first signaled that it would vote against the request for the observer status of the Palestinians at the United Nations.
But then Berlin contained itself.
Why?
Stephen Szabo: Germany does not support what the Israelites have done in Gaza.
Now, however, Germany must be careful due to its special relationship with Israel.
But at the same time, I believe that it does not support the American position either.
Germany wanted to demonstrate its independence without being too critical to Israel.
During the revolt in Libya in March 2011, Germany also abstained when it was about establishing a flight ban zone.
This was finally implemented by NATO.
Is it difficult for Germany to take a clear position on important international issues?
Yeah, that's right.
This is because it is just turning its foreign policy away from a policy, which was so-called managed by the US, to a German foreign policy.
It is difficult to add that Europeans do not have a coherent and unified policy.
So the Germans find themselves between the fronts.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to it.
I think they're still in their role, but they're on their way to a more "normal" foreign policy.
A foreign policy such as France or the United Kingdom.
What does a "normal" foreign policy mean in fact from a German point of view?
It shows the willingness to take positions independent of those of the United States or European partners in national interests.
I believe that German foreign policy is motivated by economic policy, i.e. by exports and its relations with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
Germany's economic interests are to a certain degree different from those of the other major powers and therefore Germany must protect its interests.
Have these economic interests influenced the position in the Middle East conflict and the United Nations vote?
Firstly, Germany has large markets in the Middle East, especially in the Gulf.
Therefore, it must be careful not to put the public, but also the elites in front of the Arab countries.
It certainly plays a role.
But I wouldn't want to put too much weight on it either, that's not a completely unilateral relationship.
But it certainly plays an important role in German reflections.
Has Germany damaged its relations with the United States by abstaining from voting on important decisions, such as the vote on Palestine?
I believe that in Europe and even in the United States there is a great understanding of the German position.
That is why I do not think this was as dramatic as in the Libyan question.
Perhaps Germany will even have some respect for this.
It signals that it must be taken seriously as an international player and that its interests must be considered.
There are various opinions in Europe on the Palestinian initiative.
The United States, on the other hand, has clearly voted for a veto.
Are there differences of opinion between the United States and many European nations?
Because of American internal policy, these differences have always existed.
I believe that the government under Obama in secret has quite a great deal of understanding of the European position.
But due to the political situation here, the government cannot, of course, represent this position publicly.
I believe that the actual differences of opinion are not as large as they always appear.
If you look at the relations between Obama and Prime Minister Netanyahu, Obama is not so much enthusiastic about Netanyahu's politics.
Is it difficult for Germany to agree on its close relations with Israel and the United States on the one hand, and the position of the EU's main partners on the other?
I think that is exactly what makes it so difficult for the Germans.
Of course, it would be a little easier for the Germans if there were a coherent and unified European policy, which is not currently the case.
So they cannot be part of a broader line and instead they must drive things out of their own position.
That's what they're doing with the euro.
I believe that in the future Germany will take a leading role in pushing Europe to a European position.
This is of course not easy for Germany, even because of the relationship with Israel.
This has always been a sensitive topic.
But I believe that the Germans are clear that they must play a more independent role.
Does Germany itself see itself in the role of important international players - does Germany want to take a leading role at all?
Or does Germany still find it difficult to lead?
Germany is not yet accustomed to it, this is still uncomfortable and, for obvious reasons, it is still difficult for the country to play a greater role.
